Tax collected through the first quarter of the 2021-2022 fiscal year has risen by 31.2 per cent to Ksh.416.8 billion from Ksh.317.7 billion at the same stage last year. This is according to the latest data from the National Treasury statement of actual revenues and net exchequer issues as of September 30, 2021. Meanwhile, non-tax revenues raised in the same period have grown at a slower pace of two per cent to stand at Ksh.25.4 billion in the three months in contrast to Ksh.24.9 billion last year. On a month on month basis, tax collected across September improved by 30.9 per cent to ksh.169.6 billion from Ksh.129.6 billion in September 2020. Non-tax receipts in the month however marked a rare 7.3 per cent plunge at Ksh.23.2 billion. The continued rise of tax receipts in recent months’ mirrors improved collections in a rebounding macro-economic environment following disruptions from the COVID-19 pandemic. Also Read: Tax collections took a severe hit from April last year at the onset of COVID-19 containment measures which included lock-downs, bar closures and restrictions in movement. Collections have gradually normalized on the backdrop of easing restrictions. The Kenya Revenue Authority (KRA) is expected to raise a cumulative Ksh.1.707 trillion in tax revenues by June 30 and a further Ksh.68.2 billion in non-tax revenues in the same period. At Ksh.416.8 billion, KRA has roughly met 24 per cent of its annual collection target inside three months. To hit the bull’s eye, KRA will be required to raise an average of Ksh.143.3 billion every month to June next year. Video Of The Day: Former sports CS Hassan Wario convicted over Rio games scam